"I can't believe I didn't write a review about this earlier - missed it up until now. I have this often on tap or by bottle if 90 minute or other DFH beers are not offered. This is a classic craftbeer thats made DFH famous. From notes -- A: The pour is a clear light amber color with a thin white head which dissipates to a thin layer but leaves some nice sticky lacing. S: The nose is mildly hoppy with some pine and grapefruit. There's quite a bit of toasty, bready malt in the background as well. T: The flavor is more reminiscent of a pale ale than an IPA. The bitterness is there with some nice resinous pine quality, but not all that much in the way of citrus character. The malt is again toasty and fairly pronounced on the front end. M: The body is medium with a low to moderate level of carbonation and a lingering bitterness on the tongue. D: A sessionable and nogstalic IPA."
